  "notes": "Cherokee (ᏣᎳᎩ ᎦᏬᏂᎯᏍᏗ, Tsalagi Gawonihisdi), the only Southern Iroquoian language. Written in the syllabary devised by Sequoyah (completed 1821): 85 characters, plus the later addition Ᏽ (mv), so 86 grapheme keys here; each character stands for a CV syllable (plus six bare vowels and the coda character Ꮝ /s/). Grapheme keys are the syllabary characters themselves, so no romanisation is needed as input. The romanisation letter ⟨v⟩ denotes the nasal mid-central vowel /ə̃/; ⟨d t⟩ = /t tʰ/, ⟨g k⟩ = /k kʰ/, ⟨qu⟩ = /kʷ/, ⟨dl tl⟩ = /t͡ɬ t͡ɬʰ/, ⟨ts⟩ = /t͡s/. Vowel length and the six-way tone system are NOT written in the syllabary and are therefore not represented here.",
